          "body": "Paul will not let the chapter become a history lesson. *Now not for his sake only was it written that it was credited to him, but for our sake also* (4:23-24). Genesis 15:6 is not biographical; it is canonical. The same divine pattern — believing the God who raises the dead, righteousness credited — operates now for those who believe in the God who *raised Jesus our Lord from the dead*. Abraham believed God could quicken a dead womb; Christian faith believes God did quicken a dead Christ. The God of Genesis 15 and the God of Easter morning are the same God, doing the same kind of work. And the closing couplet of 4:25 — *delivered over because of our transgressions, raised because of our justification* — names the two historical events on which the whole gospel of grace turns. Justification is not an idea; it is the verdict secured at the cross and announced at the empty tomb."
